Date: Fri, 10 May 2002 20:48:39 +0300
From: Stephen A. Berger, M.D. <mberger@post.tau.ac.il>
Source: GIDEON [edited]
<http://www.GideonOnline.com>

The following background data on pertussis in the Russian Federation were
abstracted from GIDEON.
Routine infant vaccination (DPT) is administered at ages 3, 4 to 5, 6 and
18 months.
Year / Cases reported / Vaccine coverage percent
1991 / 30 876
1992 / 24 004 / 73
1993 / 39 218 / 79
1994 / 48 614 / 88
1995 / 20 626 / 78
1996 / 13 842 / 84
1997 / 27 279 / 88
1998 / 28 045 / 91
1999 / 22 222 / 95
2000 / 29 983 / 97
--
Stephen A. Berger, M.D.
<mberger@post.tau.ac.il>
[Once again Steve Berger keeps us honest with a reminder of the
data. Thank you Steve! The reported DPT3 coverage rate of 97 percent for
2000 is impressive (DPT3 coverage rate refers to the percentage of children
less than one year of age having received 3 or more doses of DPT), but
doesn't erase the discussion of whether vaccination histories of adoptive
children should be reviewed prior to travel to their adoptive country. In
fact, this particular case highlights pockets of unvaccinated in areas that
have high overall vaccination coverages.
More information on the status of the immunization program activities in the
Russian Federation can be
found at the WHO Vaccines website:
<http://www-nt.who.int/vaccines/GlobalSummary/Immunization/CountryProfileRes
ult.cfm>
- Mod.MPP]
