[2]
Date: Sat, 11 May 2002 02:20:49 +0000
From: "padmanabhan badrinath" <badrishanthi@hotmail.com>

With reference to the posting on whooping cough in a child adopted from
Russia the moderator states "This case also begs the question of whether
childhood vaccinations should be part of pre-adoptive recommendations,
especially for children coming from countries where childhood vaccination
levels are lower".
US immigration laws already require immigrant visa applicants (including
adopted children) to obtain certain vaccinations prior to the issuance of an
immigrant visa. The vaccination requirement table from one of the US
embassies (Korea) shows that DPT is required for children aged 2 months to 6
years.
http://usembassy.state.gov/seoul/wwwh2420.html
The US government also has produced country specific flyers for prospective
parents of adopted children. The flyer for Russia is available @
http://www.travel.state.gov/adoption_russia.html
--
Dr.P.Badrinath M.D,M.Phil,(Epid)PhD(Cantab)DFPHM(UK),MPH(Distinc)
Clinical Assistant Professor & Hon Consultant in Preventive Medicine,
Department of Community Medicine,
UAE University, PO Box 17666, Al Ain,
United Arab Emirates
<badrishanthi@hotmail.com>
[Checking the weblinks provided by Dr. Badrinath is very informative. The
information for adoption of Russian children provides the names of
physicians who could care for the children if ill while waiting for
adoption, including one physician who is listed as providing vaccinations.
The document from the US Embassy in Korea clearly states the immunization
requirements for adoptive children prior to getting a visa for entry in the
USA. "Panel physicians who conduct medical examinations on behalf of
immigrant visa applicants are now required to verify that immigrant visa
applicants have met the new vaccination requirement, or that it is medically
inappropriate for the visa applicant to receive one or more of the listed
vaccinations. Certain waivers of the vaccination requirement are available
upon the recommendation of the panel physician." Given the wording of this,
one wonders if the case discussed in the previous ProMED posting was a case
that was not vaccinated because of having been granted a waiver for one of
the stated acceptable reasons. - Mod. MPP]
